On January 23, 2009, President Obama made phone calls to three foreign leaders and the Secretary General of the United Nations. He spoke with Prime Minister Harper of Canada, expressing his appreciation for Canada's friendship and his commitment to visit Canada as his first foreign visit. They discussed challenges in Afghanistan, climate change, and the global economy. President Obama also spoke with King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia, emphasizing the importance of a strong U.S.-Saudi relationship and requesting Saudi support in stopping weapons smuggling into Gaza. He also expressed interest in continuing counter-terrorism cooperation. President Obama spoke with Prime Minister Brown of the United Kingdom, expressing his desire to work together to confront the global economic crisis and discussing the situation in Gaza and the priority of Afghanistan. Lastly, President Obama spoke with UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, underscoring his commitment to a strong US-UN relationship and support for the UN's assistance mission in Iraq. They also discussed possible management reforms within the UN to improve efficiency in dealing with international problems.